{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17415484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17415484"},"attributes":{"position":50,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T09:06:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13072"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519770"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13072"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"13072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13072"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.26,0.56,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5509"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61923"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11162"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35122"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of recurrent itchy rash. The rash is most noticeable in response to heat or hot weather. He describes the appearance of raised red wheals appearing suddenly on his arms, legs, trunk, and face. Individual wheals last for up to 24 hours before resolving completely. The itching is severe, impacting his daily activities and sleep. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple raised, erythematous wheals across his trunk and limbs (Image 1, 2). The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cyclosporin","Topical corticosteroids","Loratadine","Subcutaneous omalizumab","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic spontaneous urticaria, defined by recurrent wheals occurring for more than six weeks. The wheals typically resolve within 24 hours without leaving marks. \u003Cstrong\u003ELoratadine\u003C/strong\u003E and other second-generation non-sedating antihistamines are the first-line treatment, with evidence supporting up-titration to four times the standard dose if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous omalizumab\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective second-line treatment for chronic urticaria that has failed to respond to high-dose antihistamines. It works by binding free IgE and is typically administered every four weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclosporin\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe cases that have failed both antihistamines and omalizumab. While effective, its use is limited by the need for monitoring and potential side effects including nephrotoxicity and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not effective for chronic urticaria as they cannot address the systemic nature of the condition. They may provide temporary relief for localised lesions but do not prevent new wheals from forming.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided for chronic urticaria due to the risk of serious side effects with long-term use. Short courses may occasionally be used for severe exacerbations, but should not be used as maintenance therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-sedating antihistamines are the first-line treatment for chronic urticaria, with up-titration of dose if needed","Chronic urticaria is defined as recurrent wheals lasting less than 24 hours occurring for more than six weeks","Second-line treatments for chronic urticaria include omalizumab and cyclosporin"],"references":["Dabija D, Tadi P, Danosos GN. Chronic Urticaria. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 Apr 17]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK555910/","Kolkhir P, Altrichter S, Munoz M, Hawro T, Maurer M. New treatments for chronic urticaria. Ann Allergy Asthma Immunol. 2020;124(1):2\u201312. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31446134/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61923"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13072"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20311"},{"type":"media","id":"20312"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20311"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KasTMPUD1IP4SXoCYDtsezlgtiPnew.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/KasTMPUD1IP4SXoCYDtsezlgtiPnew.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20312"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6vUg38vhOneJRRLk4DhimkrSe8lnT2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6vUg38vhOneJRRLk4DhimkrSe8lnT2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61923"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:54:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T09:41:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5509"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"